2. Management Approach 
2.1 Project Process 
In version 4 of the F-CTF system, the project focuses on overcoming the limitations of the previous version and upgrading the system architecture to improve stability, security, performance, and user experience during contest operations.
This version emphasizes solving issues that arose during usage, such as business logic errors, inaccurate challenge state management, limited load-bearing capacity, and security risks. Because the system relies heavily on processing logic and application states, the project places a strong focus on standardizing business operations, strictly controlling states, and enhancing testing to ensure the accuracy, reliability, and fairness of the system.
The application of the V-Model for the project stems from the following reasons:
a) Clear business requirements
The goals of the F-CTF version 4 system are clearly defined from the beginning, focusing on bug fixing, upgrading, and perfecting existing functions. These requirements are primarily synthesized and standardized from the actual operation of previous versions, therefore they have a high degree of stability and do not change frequently. In this context, the V-Model is a suitable choice because it allows for detailed design right from the start and closely ties each requirement to corresponding testing activities.
b) High testing demand for business logic and system states
Core components of the system, such as the Challenge Gateway, challenge initialization mechanism, and flag submission processing, must operate exactly according to the system state at any given time. Building test cases in parallel with design and development under the V-Model ensures that every function is fully verified, minimizing logic errors and state deviations during operation. The V-Model allows the implementation of testing activities at multiple levels, such as unit tests, integration tests, and system tests, attached to each design phase, thereby helping to detect potential bugs early and minimize risks during the actual deployment phase.
By applying the V-Model, the project can leverage the advantages of a highly systematic development process, suitable for clearly defined requirements and situations with a high risk of business logic errors, especially in an evaluation and competitive environment that demands high accuracy and fairness like F-CTF.
  
 
