2.2.3 Quality Control
While QA focuses on processes, Quality Control (QC) focuses on inspecting the actual product to detect and address errors that slipped through the development process.
2.2.3.1 Testing Control
Strictly adhering to the V-Model, the test control process is designed and prepared in parallel with the corresponding analysis and design phases. The testing documentation system (Test Cases) is detailed by the team in a unified format (Excel/Google Sheets) for all testing levels. This ensures that every feature and module has a clear matching scenario before writing source code and running actual tests.
The documentation system and testing levels are distributed as follows:
●	Unit Testing:
○	Documentation management: Test scenarios for each function or small module are specified in detail in an Excel file. Information fields clearly define input values, processing flows, and expected output results.
○	Execution: Based on this Excel document, programmers write automation testing source code files. These code files serve to automate the testing and comparison of the Actual Result with the documentation, ensuring the source code coverage rate reaches a minimum of 85%.
●	Integration Testing
○	Documentation management: Use Excel documents to design scenarios checking the communication and data flow between independent components/microservices (e.g., integration between Challenge Gateway, Control Server, and MariaDB/Redis databases).
○	Execution: Testers rely on the scenarios to send automated requests and check data integrity when transmitted back and forth between modules.
●	System Testing:
○	Documentation management: The Excel file synthesizes End-to-End (E2E) test scenarios based on Use Cases and User Stories, evaluating the entire system from the end-user's perspective (Admin, Contestant, Challenge Writer).
○	Execution: Thoroughly check the business flow on the interface and ensure functional requirements operate exactly as designed in the staging/production environment.
●	Non-functional Testing:
○	Documentation management: Performance and security testing scenarios are managed separately on completely distinct Excel files. The Performance Test document focuses on specifying load simulation configurations, test environment configurations, and expected metrics.
○	Execution: The testing team uses specialized and automated evaluation tools (such as K6 for load testing, Semgrep for security scanning).
●	Acceptance Testing:
○	Documentation management: Based on the SRS and user scenario, define the User Acceptance Test (UAT) document in Excel format, focusing on verifying the business goals and user satisfaction.
○	Execution: Conducted by end users (Students, Lecturers) through trial competitions or final evaluation sessions. This stage confirms that the system meets production requirements and is ready for official release.
Testing Documentation Standardization: All Excel documents across the three levels above adhere to a common template structure for easy management and defect tracking. The structure includes core information fields: Testcase ID, Objective Description, Prerequisites, Execution Steps, Expected Results, Status, and Assignee.
Defect Management Process: All defects detected from the testing levels above are recorded centrally through a management tool. Each defect report must contain full information: Steps to reproduce, attached error logs, severity level, and processing status. A defect is only closed when the Tester confirms the test scenario has run successfully on the latest build. 
