6. Configuration Management 
Configuration management plays a key role throughout the system development and deployment lifecycle, aiming to ensure that documents, source code and related tools are always managed consistently, synchronously and easily traceable among team members.
6.1 Document Management 
All project documents are managed according to a unified standard on format and storage to avoid version deviations and presentation errors. The team uses Microsoft Office and Google Docs to draft, store and share documents, test cases and test reports. Compliance with a common convention helps documents to be easy to read, easy to look up and convenient when linking with support tools such as Visio.
Secret keys and important configuration information are stored centrally with limited access rights for relevant members. Updates are performed synchronously to ensure the system operates continuously during the use of tools such as Kubernetes, Grafana, Argo Workflow or NFS Server.
Images and diagrams in documents are standardized in format to ensure consistency and ease of understanding. Changes or new content are clearly marked to support the review and evaluation process.
In addition, all arising errors are recorded according to a unified template, including error reproduction information and the person responsible for handling. The error handling process is performed sequentially from recording, fixing errors, re-testing to confirming error closure, helping to ensure the quality and stability of the system.
Error recording and management (bug) is also performed according to a unified template. Each error report must include the related testcase code, error reproduction steps, error discoverer and the assigned handler. The error handling process is clearly defined in the following steps: report error → confirm and reproduce error → assign fixer → re-test after fixing → close error when it can no longer be reproduced. This process helps ensure transparency, clear responsibility and consistency in error management throughout the project lifecycle.
6.2 Source Code Management 
The source code management process is organized according to a branching model including main branches: main, develop, release, feature and hotfix. The main branch contains stable source code currently deployed on the production environment. The develop branch is used to integrate new features during development. When implementing a new function, programmers create a branch from develop in the format v4/feature/<feature-name> and after completion it will be merged back into develop. When preparing to release a new version, the team creates the branch v4/release/v4.x.x from develop for overall testing, then merges into main. If errors arise on production, the branch v4/hotfix/<bug-name> will be created directly from main, after fixing it will be merged into both main and develop to ensure synchronization. All commits must have clear descriptive content to support traceability and review.
